      <h3>4.2 Key Performance Categories</h3>

      <h4>Training Quality</h4>
      <p>Independent reviewers generally describe the Bootcamp training as beginner-appropriate, covering account setup and basic traffic methods rather than advanced strategy. We could not verify the depth or production quality first-hand.</p>

      <h4>Commission Structure &amp; Payouts</h4>
      <p>The structure rewards recruitment and upsells more than one-off retail sales. Several third-party sources cite specific payout numbers (for example, 10% recurring on a landing-page add-on, or flat $150–$300 payouts on VIP upgrades). These figures come from sources with a financial interest in promoting sign-ups through their own referral links, so we present them as reported claims, not confirmed facts.</p>

      <h4>Community &amp; Support</h4>
      <p>A Facebook-based community and live webinars are consistently mentioned across sources as the main support channel, rather than formal one-on-one customer service.</p>

      <h4>Income Realism</h4>
      <div class="callout warn">
        <strong>Why we are cautious here:</strong> We found individual, self-published "income update" videos reporting specific cumulative earnings over time. These are self-reported by individual marketers, cannot be independently verified, and — as with any income-opportunity program — likely reflect a small, vocal subset of members rather than typical results. No legitimate review can responsibly state what a typical member earns, because that data is not publicly audited.
      </div>
    </section>

